<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-495-780  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 495 780.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IBM System User  April 1990 p41(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>High marks from S/3X users. (3X survey; includes related articleon options available to S/36 users)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McCrone, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The 1990 survey of IBM's System/3X users shows that performanceand recovery are the main issues.andP;  But, overall, users are happywith their choice of hardware and supplier with the average ratingnever falling below the acceptable mark.andP;  Over 400 respondentstook part in the survey.andP;  Of these, 45 percent work inmanufacturing or industry.andP;  Almost 60 percent do not have anylocal area networks and most are not planning to install one in1990.andP;  Nearly 25 percent say they do not have any disasterrecovery plan, 35 percent have a limited in-house disasterrecovery plan, 18 percent have strong plans, and 23 percent use adisaster recovery service.andP;  Computing budgets remain about thesame in 1990 as in 1989.andP;  Most sites have a staff of 10 or less.andO;Users are confident the machine will be around for at least a fewyears.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (products).andO;Product:   IBM System 3 (Minicomputer) (usage).andO;Topic:     Survey.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   How S/3x users rate their machines. (chart)The scores S/3X users gave their suppliers. (chart)The software running on S/3X systems. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>